    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="327"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d327">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.11 T 41/13½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <gloss type="from">Wilson</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">5 April, 1915</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I had already seen this
                    memorandum of Mr. Lansing’s.<note n="16" xml:id="d327fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_367">p. 367</ref>.</note> I
                    appreciate its force to the full. But it ought not to alter our course so long
                    as we think ourselves on the firm ground of right.</p>
                <p>It has, as Mr. Lansing points out, its bearings on the Thrasher case. That case,
                    as I said the other day, troubles me. I should very much like to know what Mr.
                    L’s view of it is. We must compound policy with legal right in wise proportions,
                    no doubt.</p>
                <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
